<subSubSection id="65158D3244FEA9DEA29AC713FB465D8C" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="0997564B89ABA9AD78710F9E81E3EC03" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
Genus 
<taxonomicName id="26FCBCD795525F0FA074B291CD0BB84C" LSID="05FE9784-88A5-1947-34A6-CA296D4A45D2" authority="Weber, 1801" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1801" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Calosoma" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Calosoma Weber, 1801</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68800F1EEA1B1EFDF1F93EFFEF9715F6" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="5CFE6A83BA51919C23BF9AF4864C2FC7" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
<taxonomicName id="52B5DFB08AEC1D33BD14102EDD943D58" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1801" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Calosoma</taxonomicName>
Weber, 1801: 20. Type species: 
<taxonomicName id="4B7EC4CADFE09FDE5F4690DAE497C6FB" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Carabus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sycophanta">
<emphasis id="52A4C5B2634E6987C711D66555F434D5" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Carabus sycophanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Linnaeus, 1758 designated by Latreille (1810: 426). Etymology (original). From the Greek 
<emphasis id="5FFEFA495AF7A033B3899898F0F470FC" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">calos</emphasis>
(beautiful) and 
<emphasis id="1DAEB5ADB783707C04FCC4F5A1E1963F" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">soma</emphasis>
(body), alluding to the beautiful body coloration of adults of 
<taxonomicName id="16288BA06663E0C4283B4572A817F973" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sycophanta">
<emphasis id="55C6CBB6EB7D78D7152771B456544869" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Calosoma sycophanta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F2965174DBF5BCAF4946DE027EB8C196" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inquisitor">
<emphasis id="4C9319A6F63E0AB957BD2652012E50C6" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Calosoma inquisitor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the two species included by Weber in the genus [neuter].
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3CEC5A4855EAFD887D112995967C4DEE" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
<taxonomicName id="2D25C5C3062B1057507E54C9B67F1738" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Callisoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Callisoma</taxonomicName>
Agassiz, 1846: 60, 61. Unjustified emendation of 
<taxonomicName id="EE4124DC749C5EA4728DC0FF13A67962" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1801" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="10EC69C73FB93FFF80C70BB5E047FA2B" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Calosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Weber, 1801.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="986263EFB4D5F5E2C306E200373DA712" lastPageId="170" lastPageNumber="171" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="diversity">
<paragraph id="2D5E8F6D6C6225D2AFD2158E0F0A939A" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="08737D0E54E21A48B2EAED49BBAB03EC" lastPageId="170" lastPageNumber="171" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
Worldwide, with about 170 species in the Nearctic (41 species, of which one is adventive), Neotropical (about 55 species, many shared with North America), Australian (three species), Oriental (six species), Palaearctic (about 45 species), an 
<pageBreakToken id="C9BAA2D6DD92CECC4810C49A2F3BD7FB" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" start="start">d</pageBreakToken>
Afrotropical (about 35 species) Regions. The species are arrayed in about 25 genus-group taxa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EFC60F0922A8934531B903D2FEDB96BA" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="identification">
<paragraph id="A42E1839EB566457BB66A107FA670A5A" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C8344F9B0BE3B3DC67D383A8FDD1B4C3" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Gidaspow (1959) revised the North American species and provided a key for their identification. Subsequently Lindroth (1961a: 50, 55) listed in synonymy some of the species that were considered valid by Gidaspow (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="8EF664D8453A694A0473D2728E7407BF" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1920" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="concretum">
<emphasis id="02FA7F3BF7B6AF11318262EA822F2986" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Calosoma concretum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0C5BCCD3CB5290A62128AFB2A016EC94" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pimelioides">
<emphasis id="C899697263F8934B602473F7CA5E639D" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Calosoma pimelioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B4034D889A1031D5421DDE81F05E38A4" baseAuthorityName="LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1847" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zimmermani">
<emphasis id="469A9B9676AECDAC49DBE8DA8B83026C" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Calosoma zimmermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and Dajoz (1997a) described a new species (
<taxonomicName id="469DE1EC6AF49CCD2C1CEBB3159F32B1" authorityName=", new combination" baseAuthorityName="Dajoz" baseAuthorityYear="1997" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dawsoni">
<emphasis id="B579195718626BB26E0ACC8D12717CEE" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Calosoma dawsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9A8120EE57E99D02433022973DA11AD7" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="taxonomic note">
<paragraph id="9E24593C0BA0A6358958157FFF89CC55" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Taxonomic Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A4B06B67E757BA891476454AD97CD735" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="C99C468F029EA07A9B7E84F2DC826F2A" authorityName="Weber" authorityYear="1801" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4DAD9D789D80804F9600998B4F42690E" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Calosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is retained here in its wide sense following several authors, including Culot (1988). Others used different arrangements. For example, Lorenz (2005) and Erwin (2007a) listed 
<taxonomicName id="AB5F5DAC70C6B81AEF7A2CEF445CC9B0" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Callisthenes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FDA7D6174F95ED3E4D8CEE7927E4BFDC" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Callisthenes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fischer von Waldheim as a valid genus with 
<taxonomicName id="908945D490D34E5DA28153D394CC257D" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Chrysostigma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ADB0DBEE6363C799D1D7ADDC585EA47A" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Chrysostigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kirby and 
<taxonomicName id="77122306A349145F262E1B633989B9EE" authorityName="Lapouge" authorityYear="1929" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Callistenia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="44E2B3468E0C1E5C04FA33AFFFBBC51F" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Callistenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lapouge as subgenera.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="19AC0132067F61228EE638320CC7A9DF" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" type="faunistic note">
<paragraph id="0B51FAF1C15AE6ABD081459B4BF5B814" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Faunistic Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5A29B109D1DA59B8C7CDE9443A1E8298" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">
Burgess and Collins (1917: 86) reported that 
<taxonomicName id="7DFD3F241EEBF0064044482D679F9076" authorityName="G. Horn" authorityYear="1876" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Calosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="170" pageNumber="171" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmeri">
<emphasis id="8BF88A7132AE38571A02439E7DC0D8C8" italics="true" pageId="170" pageNumber="171">Calosoma palmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Horn &quot;occurs in California and Mexico.&quot; The record for California is doubtful since the species, as far as known, is endemic to Guadalupe Island (Gidaspow 1959: 276).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
